NZ_CP094655.1-31	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	53917	54876	.	+	0	ID=MGA_54;product=competence type IV pilus ATPase ComGA;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_011101696.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_00530;gene=comGA;note=WP_011101696.1 competence type IV pilus ATPase ComGA (Lactiplantibacillus) [pid:43.1%25%2C q_cov:98.7%25%2C s_cov:98.1%25%2C Eval:1.5e-68],Domain:cl28318:PulE Type II secretory pathway ATPase GspE/PulE or T4P pilus assembly pathway ATPase PilB [Cell motility%2C Intracellular trafficking%2C secretion%2C and vesicular transport%2C Extracellular structures]. This model describes a protein of type IV pilus biogenesis designated PilB in Pseudomonas aeruginosa but PilF in Neisseria gonorrhoeae%3B the more common usage%2C reflected here%2C is PilB. This protein is an ATPase involved in protein export for pilin assembly and is closely related to GspE (TIGR02533) of type II secretion%2C also called the main terminal branch of the general secretion pathway. Note that type IV pilus systems are often divided into type IV-A and IV-B%2C with the latter group including bundle-forming pilus%2C mannose-sensitive hemagglutinin%2C etc. Members of this family are found in type IV-A systems. [Cell envelope%2C Surface structures%2C Protein fate%2C Protein and peptide secretion and trafficking] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:15-267%2C Eval:3.4e-77%2C score:241.9%2C C-term missing],MGA_54
NZ_CP094655.1-31	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	54893	55861	.	+	0	ID=MGA_55;product=competence type IV pilus assembly protein ComGB;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_225793059.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_00540;gene=comGB;note=WP_225793059.1 competence type IV pilus assembly protein ComGB (Streptococcus pyogenes) [pid:22.3%25%2C q_cov:87.3%25%2C s_cov:81.1%25%2C Eval:2.0e-15],Domain:cl28336:PulF Type II secretory pathway%2C component PulF [Cell motility%2C Intracellular trafficking%2C secretion%2C and vesicular transport%2C Extracellular structures]. This membrane protein is a component of the terminal branch complex of the general secretion pathway (GSP)%2C also known as the'Type II' secretion pathway. The GSP transports proteins (generally virulence-associated cell wall hydrolases) across the outer membrase of the bacterial cell. Transport across the inner membrane is often%2C but not exclusively handled by the Sec system. This model was constructed from the broader subfamily model%2C pfam00482 which includes components of pilin complexes (PilC) as well as other related genes. GspF is nearly always gene clustered with other GSP subunits. Some genes from Xylella and Xanthomonas strains score below the trusted cutoff due to excessive divergence from the family such that a sequence from Deinococcus which does not appear to be GspF scores higher. [Protein fate%2C Protein and peptide secretion and trafficking] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:29-321%2C Eval:3.0e-21%2C score:90.3%2C N-term missing],MGA_55
NZ_CP094655.1-31	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	55861	56178	.	+	0	ID=MGA_56;product=competence type IV pilus major pilin ComGC;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_003641549.1;translation=MLKKLKKRVAKGFTLVEMTIVLFIISLLILIIVPNLGAQRKHATSVNQEALVNMIQNQVELYHDDTGDVPTDLSQLEKGDYLTAKQVRQASRENITLQNGQAVVQ;locus_tag=LOCUS_00550;gene=comGC;note=WP_003641549.1 competence type IV pilus major pilin ComGC (Lactiplantibacillus) [pid:42.7%25%2C q_cov:91.4%25%2C s_cov:87.3%25%2C Eval:2.4e-15],Domain:cl26781:T2SSG Type II secretion system (T2SS)%2C protein G. The Type II secretion system%2C also called Secretion-dependent pathway (SDP)%2C is responsible for the transport of proteins across the outer membrane first exported to the periplasm by the Sec or Tat translocon in Gram-negative (diderm) bacteria. The T2SG family includes proteins such as EpsG (P45773) in Vibrio cholera%2C XcpT also called PddA (Q00514) in Pseudomonas aeruginosa or PulG (P15746)in Klebsiella pneumoniae. The PulG is thought to be anchored in the inner membrane with its C-terminus directed towards the periplasme. Together with other members of the Type II secretion machinery%2C it is thought to assemble into a pilus-like structure that may function as a dynamic mechanism to push secreted proteins out of the cell. The polypeptide is organized into a long N-terminal alpha-helix followed by a loop region that separates it from a C-terminal anti-parallel beta-sheet. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:1-104%2C Eval:4.1e-17%2C score:67.8],MGA_56
