NZ_CP094655.1-30	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	38085	39308	.	+	0	ID=MGA_1002;product=UDP-N-acetylglucosamine 1-carboxyvinyltransferase;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_002262937.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_09950;gene=murA;EC_number=2.5.1.7;note=WP_002262937.1 UDP-N-acetylglucosamine 1-carboxyvinyltransferase (Streptococcus mutans) [pid:26.3%25%2C q_cov:82.1%25%2C s_cov:83.0%25%2C Eval:3.6e-23],Domain:cl00288:EPT_RTPC-like N/A. EPSP synthase domain. 3-phosphoshikimate 1-carboxyvinyltransferase (5-enolpyruvylshikimate-3-phosphate synthase) (EC 2.5.1.19) catalyses the reaction between shikimate-3-phosphate (S3P) and phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) to form 5-enolpyruvylshkimate-3-phosphate (EPSP)%2C an intermediate in the shikimate pathway leading to aromatic amino acid biosynthesis. The reaction is phosphoenolpyruvate + 3-phosphoshikimate %3D phosphate + 5-O-(1-carboxyvinyl)-3-phosphoshikimate. It is found in bacteria and plants but not animals. The enzyme is the target of the widely used herbicide glyphosate%2C which has been shown to occupy the active site. In bacteria and plants%2C it is a single domain protein%2C while in fungi%2C the domain is found as part of a multidomain protein with functions that are all part of the shikimate pathway. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:1-272%2C Eval:2.1e-40%2C score:145.7%2C C-term missing],MGA_1002
