NZ_CP094655.1-65	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	112	747	.	+	0	ID=MGA_1651;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MEYINYQTQDQWQGPASQQSPIDIVLEQTTPRPLANQPLTVSFVGDQALTRDPRSSGDQFIGAGTLTLGNHHYHFLRLHFHDHSEHLFDGQRQDAEVHFVYQDDQGQTLVLAMLGIRAADGEAGFDFAPVINGQAGAAYLNQFFANNQGYFNYTGSLTTPPLSPDVTWVVLDAVHPFSSGSLALIHDLFANNYRAPQPITVPVYHYYESGK;locus_tag=LOCUS_16240;note=WP_038965276.1 carbonic anhydrase family protein (Bradyrhizobium diazoefficiens) [pid:33.2%25%2C q_cov:85.3%25%2C s_cov:73.6%25%2C Eval:1.7e-15%2C partial hit],Domain:cl00012:alpha_CA N/A. Carbonic anhydrase alpha%2C isozyme IX. Carbonic anhydrases (CAs) are zinc-containing enzymes that catalyze the reversible hydration of carbon dioxide in a two-step mechanism: a nucleophilic attack of a zinc-bound hydroxide ion on carbon dioxide%2C followed by the regeneration of the active site by ionization of the zinc-bound water molecule and removal of a proton from the active site. They are ubiquitous enzymes involved in fundamental processes like photosynthesis%2C respiration%2C pH homeostasis and ion transport. There are three evolutionary distinct groups - alpha%2C beta and gamma carbonic anhydrases - which show no significant sequence identity or structural similarity. Alpha CAs are strictly monomeric enzymes. The zinc ion is complexed by three histidine residues. This sub-family comprises the membrane protein CA IX. CA IX is functionally implicated in tumor growth and survival. CA IX is mainly present in solid tumors and its expression in normal tissues is limited to the mucosa of alimentary tract. CA IX is a transmembrane protein with two extracellular domains: carbonic anhydrase and%2C  a proteoglycan-like segment mediating cell-cell adhesion. There is evidence for an involvement of the MAPK pathway in the regulation of CA9 expression. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:17-199%2C Eval:2.1e-25%2C score:96.3%2C N-term missing],MGA_1651
NZ_CP094655.1-65	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	940	3444	.	-	0	ID=MGA_1652;product=ATP-grasp domain-containing protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_003645061.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_16250;note=WP_003645061.1 ATP-grasp domain-containing protein (Lactiplantibacillus) [pid:33.4%25%2C q_cov:94.4%25%2C s_cov:91.6%25%2C Eval:5.1e-124],Domain:cl27719:Biotin_carb_N Biotin carboxylase%2C N-terminal domain. Carbamoyl-phosphate synthase (CPSase) catalyzes the first committed step in pyrimidine%2C arginine%2C and urea biosynthesis. In general%2C it is a glutamine-dependent enzyme%2C EC 6.3.5.5%2C termed CPSase II in eukaryotes. An exception is the mammalian mitochondrial urea-cycle form%2C CPSase I%2C in which the glutamine amidotransferase domain active site Cys on the small subunit has been lost%2C and the enzyme is ammonia-dependent. In both CPSase I and the closely related%2C glutamine-dependent CPSase III (allosterically activated by acetyl-glutamate) demonstrated in some other vertebrates%2C the small and large chain regions are fused in a single polypeptide chain. This model represents the large chain of glutamine-hydrolysing carbamoyl-phosphate synthases%2C or the corresponding regions of larger%2C multifunctional proteins%2C as found in all domains of life%2C and CPSase I forms are considered exceptions within the family. In several thermophilic species (Methanobacterium thermoautotrophicum%2C Methanococcus jannaschii%2C Aquifex aeolicus)%2C the large subunit appears split%2C at different points%2C into two separate genes. [Purines%2C pyrimidines%2C nucleosides%2C and nucleotides%2C Pyrimidine ribonucleotide biosynthesis] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:5-391%2C Eval:7.4e-53%2C score:186.4],Domain:cl27719:Biotin_carb_N Biotin carboxylase%2C N-terminal domain. Carbamoyl-phosphate synthase (CPSase) catalyzes the first committed step in pyrimidine%2C arginine%2C and urea biosynthesis. In general%2C it is a glutamine-dependent enzyme%2C EC 6.3.5.5%2C termed CPSase II in eukaryotes. An exception is the mammalian mitochondrial urea-cycle form%2C CPSase I%2C in which the glutamine amidotransferase domain active site Cys on the small subunit has been lost%2C and the enzyme is ammonia-dependent. In both CPSase I and the closely related%2C glutamine-dependent CPSase III (allosterically activated by acetyl-glutamate) demonstrated in some other vertebrates%2C the small and large chain regions are fused in a single polypeptide chain. This model represents the large chain of glutamine-hydrolysing carbamoyl-phosphate synthases%2C or the corresponding regions of larger%2C multifunctional proteins%2C as found in all domains of life%2C and CPSase I forms are considered exceptions within the family. In several thermophilic species (Methanobacterium thermoautotrophicum%2C Methanococcus jannaschii%2C Aquifex aeolicus)%2C the large subunit appears split%2C at different points%2C into two separate genes. [Purines%2C pyrimidines%2C nucleosides%2C and nucleotides%2C Pyrimidine ribonucleotide biosynthesis] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:553-629%2C Eval:6.6e-08%2C score:52.7%2C C-term missing],MGA_1652
